**Definition 7.1 (Memory Graph).** A memory graph is a tuple $G = (I, R, E, \tau)$ where: 
- $I$ is a finite set of **items** (named, typed memory units);
- $R = \bigcup_{i \in I} R_i$ is the set of all **revisions**, where $R_i = (r_i^{(1)}, r_i^{(2)}, \ldots)$ is the ordered append-only revision sequence for item $i$;
- $E \subseteq R \times \mathrm{EdgeType} \times R$ is a set of typed, directed edges between revisions;
- $\tau : \mathrm{TagName} \rightharpoonup R$ is a partial function mapping tag names to revisions (the mutable pointer layer).

Each revision $r_i^{(k)}$ is **immutable**: once created, its content $\phi(r_i^{(k)})$ cannot be modified. Tags are the sole mutable component [@Park2026Kumiho, Def. 7.1].
